[{"id":"VR930945","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Two figures are shown, labeled Before Interaction and After Interaction. Each figure shows an x y plane with an electron, represented by a gray circle, and a photon, represented by a wave. In the Before Interaction figure, the electron is at rest at the origin, and the photon has wavelength lambda sub 0 and is moving horizontally to the right along the x axis, towards the origin. In the After Interaction figure, the electron is below the x axis and to the right of the y axis, moving downward and to the right, and the photon is above the positive x axis and to the right of the y axis, moving upward and to the right. A note states that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR930945.g04.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A photon of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> moves in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive x\"><math alttext=\"positive x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>-direction toward an electron that is initially at rest, as shown in the “Before Interaction” figure. The photon and electron interact. The resulting photon of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub></math></span></span> and the electron move in the directions shown in the “After Interaction” figure. Which of the following correctly compares <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub></math></span></span> to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> and provides a valid justification?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR930945_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f equals lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f equals lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>, because the photon momentum has a positive <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-component before and after the interaction.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f equals lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f equals lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>, because the photon energy is the same before and after the interaction.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f is greater than lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f is greater than lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>, because the photon momentum has a positive <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"y\"><math alttext=\"y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>y</mi></math></span></span>-component after the interaction.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f is greater than lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f is greater than lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>, because the energy of the photon-electron system is the same before and after the interaction.</p>"],"answer":3}]